  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money appear legitimate by passing it through a series of transactions or business dealings. This activity is explicitly criminalized under various national and international laws.\n\nFor example:\n\n- **United States**: The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the Money Laundering Control Act (1986) criminalize money laundering. The USA PATRIOT Act further strengthened these regulations.\n- **European Union**: The EU has implemented several Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Directives to combat money laundering across member states.\n- **International Standards**: The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Countries that are members of FATF are required to implement AML laws in line with these standards.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. The severity of the penalties often depends on the amount of money involved, the jurisdiction, and the specifics of the case. \n\nIn summary, money laundering is a serious crime with substantial legal consequences.",
